abstract: The Layton House, at Milford, N.J., one of the oldest taverns and landmarks in that part of the State, was destroyed by fire early yesterday morning. The outhouses, which were close to the tavern, were struck by lightning, the fire spreading to the house. Everything, including a horse and two head of cattle, was consumed. The loss will probably reach $9,000. The furniture only is insured.

abstract: Mr. Beecher preached his farewell sermon --the last before his annual trip to the White Mountains--yesterday. If he was suffering from "hay fever" he showed no sign of it in his face, which never looked ruddier or more healthful. He smiled benevolently as he climbed into his place between the two rosebushes that flanked the platform, and gave out a text that bore no especial reference to what followed.

abstract: ST. PAUL, Minn., July 14.--The present crisis in the growth of the wheat crop has apparently passed, though the next 10 days will be full of possibilities of danger. For two days the weather has been moderately cool, with bright sun and brisk, drying winds, the reverse of the warm, damp, murky weather that caused so much alarm before. Reports from all over the State are all of a more hopeful character.

abstract: LONDON, July 28.--A correspondent says: "There is reason to believe that the House of Lords will not reject the Compensation bill.
